{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623281"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:09:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:09:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16856"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16856"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.62,0.13,0.09,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76338"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9546"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16856"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61847"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7879"},{"type":"tags","id":"8091"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"},{"type":"tags","id":"9838"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22558"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76338"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVon Willebrand factor is a large multimeric protein that plays several important roles in haemostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a role of Von Willebrand factor?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activating vitamin K","Stabilising factor VIII","Facilitating the extrinsic coagulation pathway","Activating tissue factor","Limiting platelet aggregation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVon Willebrand factor has several important functions, with \u003Cstrong\u003Estabilising factor VIII\u003C/strong\u003E being one of its key roles. It acts as a carrier protein that protects factor VIII in the circulation, allowing it to be available for activation when needed as part of the clotting cascade. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivating vitamin K\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a function of Von Willebrand factor. Vitamin K is activated by vitamin K epoxide reductase\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitating the extrinsic coagulation pathway\u003C/strong\u003E - Von Willebrand factor is not directly involved in the extrinsic pathway\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivating tissue factor\u003C/strong\u003E - Tissue factor is activated by vessel injury, not by Von Willebrand factor\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELimiting platelet aggregation\u003C/strong\u003E - Von Willebrand factor actually promotes rather than limits platelet aggregation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe second major role of Von Willebrand factor is to enable platelet adhesion to exposed collagen and facilitate platelet-platelet binding. This is particularly important in areas of high blood flow where direct platelet-collagen interactions would be insufficient for effective platelet adhesion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Von Willebrand factor enables platelet adhesion to exposed collagen under high shear conditions.","Von Willebrand factor plays a key role in supporting the intrinsic pathway of the clotting cascade","Von Willebrand factor acts as a carrier protein that stabilises factor VIII in circulation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Cortes GA, Moore MJ, El-Nakeep S. Physiology, Von Willebrand Factor. [Updated 2023 Feb 20]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559062/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61847"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16856"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61847"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T08:36:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T08:37:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9546"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76338"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"